<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH; FAIR OFFERS CHECKUPS FOR CHILDREN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It may not be your average fair with rides and prizes, but it will help ensure 
your child's good health. It is the 5th annual Kids Care Fair, at which 
children ages 2 months to 4 years can receive free immunizations to protect 
them from polio, tetanus, measles and other preventable childhood diseases. 
</P>
<P>
 Children through age 18 can also have a free basic health screening that 
includes blood pressure, vision and hearing tests. 
</P>
<P>
 "The recent increase of tuberculosis cases and prevalence of other preventable 
childhood diseases unfortunately acts as a reminder of the importance of 
immunizing children before the age of 2," said Joan McCandless, project 
director of Kids Care Fair. 
</P>
<P>
 Information on HIV/AIDS, prenatal health care, lead poisoning, eating 
disorders and nutrition will also be available. 
</P>
<P>
 The screenings will be held Saturday at: 
</P>
<P>
 * Community Housing Services Head Start, 725 W. Altadena Drive, Altadena, 9 
a.m. to 3 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * Pomona Unified School District headquarters, 800 S. Garey Ave., Pomona, 9 
a.m. to 1 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, in English, Spanish, Chinese, Korean or Vietnamese, call 
(800) 870-KIDS. 
</P>
