<LENGTH>
<P>
744 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCOTT HARRIS: ANTI-ABORTION MAIL SHOWS IT CAN HAPPEN HERE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SCOTT HARRIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In lieu of flowers, Planned Parenthood of Los Angeles had a suggestion for 
people who wanted to express their feelings about the recent deaths of Dr. John 
Bayard Britton and his 75-year-old bodyguard in Pensacola, Fla. You may recall 
that Dr. Britton and James Barrett, a retired Air Force lieutenant colonel, 
were shotgunned at close range, allegedly by an anti-abortion zealot who had 
claimed such actions constitute justifiable homicide. 
</P>
<P>
 A few days after the killings, Planned Parenthood sent a fund-raising letter 
to 150,000 households. This may seem a bit exploitative. Then again, it seems 
safe to assume that Dr. Britton and Mr. Barrett would have appreciated the 
gesture. 
</P>
<P>
 "Dear Pro-Choice Friend," it began. "Tragedy has struck again. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
 Some recipients, it seems, didn't appreciate the appeal. One was returned with 
this scrawled on the bottom: 
</P>
<P>
 How did you baby killing bastards get my name?  
</P>
<P>
 Take me off your mailing list at once!  
</P>
<P>
 May you all burn in hell!  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Planned Parenthood shared some of their more colorful correspondence with me, 
I suspect, because they couldn't fulfill my original request. Ever since the 
point-blank shotgun slayings of Dr. Britton, 69, and Barrett, I'd been hoping 
to meet a doctor who would tell me what it is like living in fear of 
God-fearing, gunslinging wackos out there. You don't have to travel to 
Pensacola to have a brush with the jihad. When they told me how one of their 
physicians was followed home and subjected to a protest outside her front door, 
I figured she'd be a fine interview. But it was no go. Even with assurances of 
anonymity, Planned Parenthood officials tell me, doctors who perform abortions 
are extremely wary of public attention. 
</P>
<P>
 "They've seen one of their own shot in the head in the last month, so how can 
you blame them?" said Suellen B. Wood, executive director of the agency's Los 
Angeles operations. "It strikes close to home." 
</P>
<P>
 So they showed me the mail instead, further impressing the point that, yes, it 
could happen here. Less than a year ago, a Bakersfield clinic that performs 
abortions was torched -- one of 87 acts of arson since 1977 chronicled in a 
recent report by the National Abortion Federation. That report, issued before 
the slayings of Britton and Barrett, noted the March, 1993, murder of Dr. David 
Gunn, also in Pensacola, and the August, 1993, nonfatal shooting of Dr. George 
Tiller in Wichita, Kan., as well as 37 bombings, 91 assaults and 178 death 
threats. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead of a doctor, Planned Parenthood suggest I talk with the director of a 
San Fernando Valley clinic, who had previously allowed her name to be used in 
the press. This director, it turned out, had changed her policy. She requested 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
 Shock, she said, was the immediate reaction to the slaying of Dr. Britton. 
After the shooting of Dr. Gunn, she explained, she could comfort herself with 
the belief that it was the act of a single lunatic. These slayings erased the 
comfort zone. 
</P>
<P>
 But it would be wrong to suggest that fear pervades the clinics. Security 
precautions are "part of the daily routine." Workers survey the parking lot for 
suspicious characters. They try to enter and leave the building in pairs. They 
remove name tags and surgical gear to mask their identity. "After awhile, 
you're not thinking about the reasons you're doing this," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 The occasional homicide is a good reminder. 
</P>
<P>
 The fund-raising effort, Wood says, has been going well. But the most profound 
impact of the recent shootings is how it has further splintered abortion rights 
opponents. Officials in Operation Rescue, the anti-abortion group known for its 
militant tactics, have acknowledged that violence perpetrated in the name of 
stopping "baby killers" has alienated many former supporters. 
</P>
<P>
 Wood said she appreciated the fact that several people responded to misfired 
fund-raising letters with thoughtful letters explaining why they abhor abortion 
and abhor the violence of extremists. 
</P>
<P>
 Wood says that Planned Parenthood intends to write back, hopeful that she can 
find some "common ground" with those who argue that the best means of birth 
control isn't abortion, but rather education and the promotion of abstinence. 
Wood says she intends to point out that Planned Parenthood spends 95% of its 
budget on education and other matters, trying to make abortion a last resort. 
</P>
<P>
 "We very much appreciate," she said, "those folks who are thoughtful about 
what they do." 
</P>
</TEXT>
