<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLUMN LEFT/ ALEXANDER COCKBURN: BIG LABOR GIVES WORKERS EMPTY WORDS; GLOBAL 
CAPITALISM RULES ALL; UNIONS MUST ACT GLOBALLY AS WELL, OR LABOR DAY IS A JOKE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEXANDER COCKBURN, Alexander Cockburn writes for the Nation and other 
publications. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 When the last $20-an-hour jobs are gone, when the eight-hour day for which so 
many fought for so long is but a distant memory, when strikes are legally 
banned, the Wagner Act tossed in the trash can and America a land of $6-an-hour 
part-time jobs with no benefits or security, what will they do with Labor Day 
or May Day, which used to be celebrations of the might of organized labor and 
the hopes of working people? 
</P>
<P>
 Oh, they'll linger on no doubt, as holidays whose original source and meaning 
have long since been forgotten, or part of dimly remembered folklore. Maybe 
some older knight of labor with a sense of history will evoke memories of a 
more glorious and combative past, when unions were a mighty power in the land. 
</P>
<P>
 What would such a knight of labor tell the working folk? We have the text. 
</P>
<P>
 "We were never meant to be beggars at the table of wealth. We were never meant 
to be the apostles of labor cannibalism on the world stage. We were meant for a 
higher destiny. We were never meant to be the lieutenants of capitalism. We 
were never meant to be the pallbearers of the workers of the world." 
</P>
<P>
 The man who uttered these powerful revolutionary sentiments is a mainstream 
Big Labor chieftain: Jack Henning, executive secretary-treasurer of the 
California Labor Federation, addressing the biennial convention of the state 
AFL-CIO in Sacramento last month.  
</P>
<P>
 Henning began by citing the "never-ending conflict between labor and 
employers," which continues into the present era of global capitalism, in which 
"American capital spits on the American flag" when doing so suits its purpose. 
</P>
<P>
 "It is the human disposition to resist tyranny," Henning said. "In the 
cesspools of 19th-Century capitalism, there came a response, modern unionism. 
There was another reply. In 1848, Karl Marx issued the Communist Manifesto, 
which called on the workers of the world. He said, 'Unite, you have nothing to 
lose but your chains.' The resulting movement, however flawed, had a vision of 
global unionism." 
</P>
<P>
 Henning narrated the collapse of Soviet communism and the failure of 
non-communist labor unions to build a militant global response to international 
capital. In each country, labor sought only national self-interest. "An 
example: When AT&T transferred all of its phone-set manufacturing to Singapore 
for the low wages, for the long hours, the Singaporean labor movement embraced 
that. In response to an AFL-CIO protest, they said what labor nationalism 
always says: 'We take care of ours, you take care of yours.' We were meant for 
something more than that!"  
</P>
<P>
 Global capitalism, Henning said, rules America today, and the titans of the 
corporate system -- General Motors, General Electric, the big banks -- bestride 
the world. Their power in Washington shapes trade policy. To labor, Washington 
offers nothing: The North American Free Trade Agreement was proof of that. "The 
two-party system can't give relief because capitalism . . . finances both."  
</P>
<P>
 Henning concluded that the AFL-CIO should issue a convention call to all the 
unions of the now-prevailing free world. "At that convention, there could be 
chartered treaties and accords of defense to ban and abolish the cannibalism 
that becomes necessary when capital controls the respective societies of the 
nations of the world. Global unionism is the answer to global capitalism. There 
is no other way." 
</P>
<P>
 A fine speech. It could serve well as the standard text for flights of oratory 
in future Labor Days. But it does raise the question posed by all such bursts 
of tremendous rhetoric: What connection do these words have with reality? Alas, 
not much. 
</P>
<P>
 Henning, now in his late 70s, has long been delivering intermittent bursts of 
fiery sentiments. But between speeches, life goes on as usual. The state 
AFL-CIO endorses Democrats, many of whom duly sell out labor. In the executive 
suites of the state labor federation, ideas of how to mobilize workers in 
California gather dust. 
</P>
<P>
 The AFL-CIO whose international reputation Henning lauded is loathed by union 
organizers in the Third World as the sponsor, along with the Central 
Intelligence Agency, of such outfits as the American Institute for Free Labor 
Development, whose role is to destroy just the sort of radical unionism Henning 
calls for. 
</P>
<P>
 The problem with political rhetoric in America is that no one believes it. 
Beautiful words pour from the speaker's mouth, while reality takes another bite 
out of the seat of his trousers. 
</P>
<P>
 So come on, Jack! Denounce the AFL-CIO national leadership. Get with Tony 
Mazzocchi of the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers and form that working 
people's party you've both been calling for. Don't just talk, do something 
real. 
</P>
</TEXT>
