<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIGH SCHOOL SAT RESULTS A MIXED BAG FOR COUNTY; EDUCATION: COLLEGE-BOUND 
SENIORS SHOW FAR BETTER MATH SKILLS THAN VERBAL. SOME CAMPUSES SHOWED LARGE 
DECLINES IN BOTH. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAIA DAVIS and TRACY WILSON, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura County high schools showed mixed results on the latest Scholastic 
Aptitude Tests, with Simi Valley and Camarillo high schools scoring the most 
substantial gains and Ventura High posting an alarming drop. 
</P>
<P>
 Mirroring state and national trends, college-bound seniors who took the SAT at 
county high schools last spring performed far better in the math portion than 
the verbal. 
</P>
<P>
 Some schools showed substantial declines in both areas. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura High School's scores plunged 42 points in verbal skills, from 440 to 
398, and 33 points in math, from 492 to 459. 
</P>
<P>
 The sharp drops, the biggest posted by any county school, took Ventura High 
from being above the state average to below in both the math and verbal 
sections. The California average was 482 in math and 413 in verbal skills. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura Unified School District officials said Wednesday they are unable to 
explain the performance of the 398 Ventura High seniors who took the test last 
spring. 
</P>
<P>
 But they plan to beef up their college-prep curriculum or take any other steps 
necessary to help students earn the high SAT scores crucial for admission to 
many of the nation's best colleges. 
</P>
<P>
 "We are taking a serious look at what's happening at the school," said Arlene 
Miro, the district's director of administrative services. 
</P>
<P>
 Typically, only the brightest and most ambitious students take the SAT, which 
are designed solely as a tool for college-admissions directors. Although the 
number of students who took the tests in Ventura County's schools was 
unavailable Wednesday, state education officials reported that 46% of 
California seniors sat through the rigorous 2 1/2-hour exam. 
</P>
<P>
 Graded on a scale of 200 to 800 points, the SAT's verbal portion measures 
knowledge of vocabulary and reading comprehension. The math section contains 
problems in arithmetic, algebra and geometry. 
</P>
<P>
 In Ventura County, Thousand Oaks High had an average math score of 551 -- the 
best in the county and nearly 70 points above the state average of 482. 
</P>
<P>
 As was true around the state and the nation, Thousand Oaks boys scored better 
in math than girls. Boys at the school averaged 575 in math contrasted with 507 
for male students statewide, while Thousand Oaks High girls scored an average 
of 526 contrasted with the California average of 461. 
</P>
<P>
 Conejo Valley Unified School District officials attributed the school's good 
math results to demanding teachers, well-educated parents and toughened 
graduation requirements that force students to take a heavier load of academic 
classes. 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo High School students achieved the highest average verbal score in 
the county, 486, 73 points higher than the state average. 
</P>
<P>
 Because of the importance of SAT scores for students' college admission and 
for a school's public image, Principal Terry Tackett said Camarillo High took 
steps last school year to improve seniors' performance. 
</P>
<P>
 Camarillo High encouraged its seniors to take SAT-preparation courses offered 
by private companies after school hours. 
</P>
<P>
 And during school hours, English teachers came up with one vocabulary word per 
day that teachers in all subjects were expected to integrate into their 
instruction. 
</P>
<P>
 "All year they have stressed vocabulary and reading," Tackett said. 
</P>
<P>
 Simi Valley High's average verbal score improved by 15 points, from 434 to 
449, and its results in math went up slightly from 520 to 524. 
</P>
<P>
 But far fewer Simi Valley High students took the test this year than last -- 
167 versus 204 -- which school officials blame on the Jan. 17 earthquake that 
caused severe damage around the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials at the College Board, which publishes the SAT, maintain that the 
smaller the percentage of students that take the test at a particular school 
the better the average scores, because in general the highest-achievers sit for 
the exam. 
</P>
<P>
 Most Simi Valley High students took the SAT in the months after the quake, 
which damaged their school so badly they had to move their classes across town 
to Royal High. 
</P>
<P>
 "You have to remember, in Simi we were dramatically affected by the 
earthquake," said Rebecca Wetzel, Simi Valley Unified School District program 
director. 
</P>
<P>
 In Fillmore, the other Ventura County city severely affected by the quake, the 
high school was not substantially damaged and SAT scores declined slightly from 
the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
 Considering the small percentage of a school's enrollment that takes the exam, 
Santa Paula Union High School Principal Sandra Barbier said she is concerned 
about the public judging the success of a school on the basis of 
college-entrance exams. 
</P>
<P>
 "I really hate to see the measure of a school based on an SAT score," Barbier 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Paula Union High's verbal score of 415 was about even with the state 
average, while its math score of 454 is nearly 30 points below the California 
average. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite such concerns as Barbier's, college admissions officials said they 
give the exams high priority when deciding whom to admit to their schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Grading standards and curricula differ from school to school, said Ernie 
Sandlin, director of admission at Cal Lutheran University in Thousand Oaks. But 
SATs are the same across the country. 
</P>
<P>
 They are our "one standard piece of information," Sandlin said. "They're 
extremely important." At Cal Lutheran, the average SAT score for this year's 
incoming freshmen is 450 verbal and 480 math, he said. Average SAT Scores in 
County 05,23,08,08,08,08 Districts *2*1992-93 *2*1993-94 and schools Math 
