<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OXNARD; MANAGER OF STORE CLEARED IN SHOOTING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An Oxnard store manager who shot and wounded a suspected shoplifter on Aug. 4 
was justified because the teen-ager threatened an employee with a knife, 
prosecutors have concluded. 
</P>
<P>
 "I felt that under the circumstances, it was reasonable for him to respond 
with deadly force," Deputy Dist. Atty.Donald M. Grant said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Ibrahim Himideh, 33, manager of Oxnard Ranch Market, fired one bullet from a 
.25-caliber semiautomatic handgun and struck the 16-year-old suspect as the 
youth was lunging at a store employee, police have said. 
</P>
<P>
 The youth was treated for a gunshot wound at St. John's Regional Medical 
Center. Authorities have refused to comment on the severity of the wound. 
</P>
<P>
 Oxnard Detective Mike Palmier said an employee had followed the suspect to the 
parking lot after seeing the youth take three cans of styling mousse. 
</P>
<P>
 A confrontation ensued, authorities said, during which the 16-year-old 
displayed a knife and made a move toward the employee, prompting Himideh to 
fire. GREG RIPPEE 
</P>
</TEXT>
