<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: HOLLYWOOD; REPORT ASKED 
ON ALL DAMAGE FROM SUBWAY CONSTRUCTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 County Supervisor Mike Antonovich Wednesday asked for a report of all damage 
caused by Metro Rail subway construction from Union Station to Hollywood, 
including a cost estimate for curing the economic and physical impacts of the 
massive project. 
</P>
<P>
 The request was made by Antonovich during a meeting of the Metropolitan 
Transportation Board, on which he serves.It came six days after tunneling was 
shut down because a section of Hollywood Boulevard sank up to nine inches, 
buckling the Walk of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
 "A pattern of construction difficulties beginning from Union Station, where 
undetected high ground water tables impeded construction . . . to the discovery 
of hydrogen sulfide and methane gas in the Mid-City area raise questions about 
whether planning and oversight have been properly managed," said Antonovich, 
who favors construction of a monorail instead of a subway through the San 
Fernando Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 Alan Sieroty, a former state senator who owns property along Hollywood 
Boulevard, urged the MTA board, "Don't let the administrators sweep this under 
the rug as just another little thing. . . . It really bothers me that you don't 
take responsibility for what you did."  
</P>
<P>
 MTA officials believe the sinking was caused by loosely packed, sandy soil and 
leaking water pipes. They say they have yet to determine the cause of the water 
leaks, but said they may have been caused by Jan. 17 earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 Leron Gubler, general manager of the Hollywood Chamber of Commerce, called for 
an independent investigation by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is an international cultural resource," he said, citing news reports 
about the damage from as far away as Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
