<HEADLINE>
<P>
MAN KILLED WHEN VEHICLE FLIPS OVER ON FREEWAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 55-year-old Anaheim man died Wednesday when his utility vehicle flipped over 
several times on the Golden State Freeway, smashing in the driver's side of the 
vehicle, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 The man, whose name was not released pending notification of his family, was 
heading north shortly before 10 a.m. in the right lane, just north of the 
Hollywood Freeway, when he decided to switch lanes, said Officer Rich Obregon 
of the California Highway Patrol. 
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, a vehicle from the fast lane was also trying to switch to 
the middle lane. The two cars did not collide, Obregon said, but the drivers 
saw each other and pulled quickly back into their original lanes. 
</P>
<P>
 However, the man in the utility vehicle pulled back too hard, sending the car 
into a spin, Obregon said. The car flipped over more than three times and slid 
on its rooftop to a stop, he added. 
</P>
<P>
 Obregon said the man was pronounced dead at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
 Two children in the car -- the man's 12-year-old daughter and a 17-year-old 
boy -- suffered minor injuries and were released from area hospitals, Obregon 
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
