<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; CITY WARNED OF HOUSING PROPOSAL ON AMMO SITE; 
DEVELOPMENT: CRITICS CITE LIKELY LEFTOVER TOXIC MATERIAL IN THE SOIL AND A ROAD 
SYSTEM THAT IS EXPECTED TO BRING NOISE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DOUGLAS ALGER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dozens of residents here are sending up a flare about a massive residential 
development to be built on the site of an old munitions factory in the center 
of the city. 
</P>
<P>
 Several people warned the City Council at its meeting Tuesday that the 
2,911-unit Porta Bella housing project is fraught with potential liability for 
the city because of likely leftover contamination on the property and a 
questionable road system. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not opposed to development. We're opposed to this type of development," 
said Christopher Townsley, a Placerita Canyon resident. "We don't like it being 
ramrodded down our throat." 
</P>
<P>
 As proposed by Northholme Partners, Porta Bella includes 1,667 condominiums 
and 1,244 single-family homes to be built on 996 acres south of Soledad Canyon 
Road and east of San Fernando Road in the Saugus area. It includes a 27-acre 
business park, 450 acres of preserved open space and land set aside for Santa 
Clarita's future civic center. 
</P>
<P>
 Porta Bella is the largest residential development project in Santa Clarita's 
seven-year history. It was approved by the city Planning Commission in June and 
is scheduled for a series of public hearings before the council. 
</P>
<P>
 Critics, led by residents of the nearby Circle J Ranch community, note the 
likelihood of toxic material remaining in the soil. The Whittaker Corp. 
manufactured and tested ammunition, explosives and flares there from 1906 to 
1987. 
</P>
<P>
 The possibility of heavy metals being in the soil was raised by the draft 
environmental impact report prepared for the project in 1993, as were concerns 
that Porta Bella will cut into a major ridgeline and add traffic to already 
busy streets. 
</P>
<P>
 The state Department of Toxic Substances Control and the federal Environmental 
Protection Agency have identified 14 distinct spots at the site containing 
waste of munitions-related byproducts. Whittaker has cleared 13 of them, so 
far, to the satisfaction of authorities. 
</P>
<P>
 Sixty-four other sites have been identified as having possible contamination. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Clarita officials have long said they will require Whittaker Corp. to be 
liable for any future toxic problems at the site, but residents said lawsuits 
would undoubtedly be directed against anyone considered negligent. 
</P>
<P>
 "I have a 2-year-old son," said resident Renee Sabol. "If anything happens to 
my son because of negligence, God help them." 
</P>
<P>
 Residents also are concerned about the road system proposed through the 
property, including elevated overpasses that are expected to bring traffic 
noise to the nearby community. 
</P>
<P>
 "We saw what happens to overpasses in the earthquake," said Dean Cheeseman, a 
Circle J Ranch resident. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Porta Bella's developers say the project provides Santa Clarita with needed 
infrastructure, including a better network of roads that may actually deflect 
traffic from the Circle J Ranch community. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want this project to be successful," said Sam Veltri, project manager. "I 
believe we have demonstrated that with our planning process." 
</P>
<P>
 Council members Tuesday agreed that both the toxic contamination and road 
system issues must be addressed before Porta Bella will be considered for 
approval. They are scheduled to visit the Porta Bella site at 7 a.m. Sept. 24, 
in a tour that is open to the public. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're interested in doing this one right," said Councilwoman Jo Anne Darcy. 
"If it's not right, we won't pass it." 
</P>
<P>
 More News 
</P>
<P>
 . . . about the Antelope and Santa Clarita valleys. B10,B11 
</P>
</TEXT>
