1198 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLOTHES MAKE THE STUDENT, SCHOOLS DECIDE; EDUCATION: LONG BEACH PUPILS WILL 
WEAR UNIFORMS STARTING IN SEPTEMBER. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By J. MICHAEL KENNEDY and NICHOLAS RICCARDI, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The uniforms are coming. 
</P>
<P>
 What was once the domain of the parochial school is making its move into the 
world of public education -- with the blessing of the state. 
</P>
<P>
 For the likes of Jesus Cervantes of Long Beach, the uniform revolution means 
trading in his T-shirt and baggy shorts for navy blue pants and a white polo 
shirt. 
</P>
<P>
 For Santa Ana fifth-grader Maria Gomez, it means bowing to her mom's fashion 
wishes. 
</P>
<P>
 And for Yolanda Vasquez, a Sun Valley parent, it means a quick way to "tell 
the bad people from the good." 
</P>
<P>
 From the malls to the schoolyards, standardized school clothes were a top 
subject of conversation Wednesday, one day after Gov. Pete Wilson signed into 
law a bill allowing school districts to choose the uniformed approach. 
</P>
<P>
 A number of school districts around the state, including some in Southern 
California, have had voluntary uniforms for some time. And school districts 
around the nation are taking a serious look at what might have been unthinkable 
before the era of gang colors. 
</P>
<P>
 And nowhere are uniforms making a bigger sartorial splash than in Long Beach, 
where the school board in January, citing concerns over gang-style attire in 
the classroom, ordered mandatory uniforms for its 57,000 elementary and middle 
school students. 
</P>
<P>
 When the policy goes into effect next month, it will mark the first time that 
a major U.S. city has made uniforms standard dress for its public schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Some may protest, but there is no question that Mary Marquez is a believer. 
She is the principal of Long Beach's Whittier Elementary School, which has been 
experimenting with voluntary uniforms for five years. 
</P>
<P>
 During that time, the school, in an economically depressed part of the city, 
has gradually improved in a number of academic areas. And it was announced this 
week that Whittier had the lowest absentee rate of Long Beach's 82 schools. 
Marquez attributes part of that success to the uniforms, which she said make 
for a much more even playing field when it comes to clothes. And there is no 
confusion about a child unwittingly wearing gang-style garb to school. 
</P>
<P>
 "The parents are pleased to have something worn that can't be mistaken for 
gang attire," she said. "The teachers are very happy with it, that kids come to 
school ready to learn. No one thing is going to fix everything, but it is an 
important step in making the students feel like they are a part of things." 
</P>
<P>
 Not that all are in agreement about the value of the uniform. Some, for 
instance, complain about the cash outlay for the special clothes, while others 
say they stifle the creativity of the children. 
</P>
<P>
 Critics have also contended that if uniforms are imposed, then students will 
find some other method of expression, such as expensive jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
 "In adolescence, identity and attire are related," said Ted Mitchell, dean of 
the UCLA School of Education. "One's identity is a lot about dress, so it 
complicates matters some." 
</P>
<P>
 The American Civil Liberties Union has come out against uniforms, and so has 
Jesus Cervantes. 
</P>
<P>
 Jesus, a 14-year-old eighth-grader at Mary Butler Middle School, was dressed 
Wednesday in a Colorado Rockies T-shirt and baggy shorts. He wasn't buying the 
official line on the need for uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're not gangbangers," he said. "We just want to be kids and have fun." 
</P>
<P>
 Later, in the outdoor lunch area, a group of students gathered and offered 
further critiques. Some pointed out that one of the required colors -- blue -- 
is the shade favored by one of the city's biggest gangs. Other decried the 
monotony of their wardrobes since the uniforms came into vogue. "It's like the 
same thing every day for lunch, breakfast and dinner," said January Prince, 10, 
a sixth-grader. 
</P>
<P>
 The Mary Butler uniform is a white top and navy skirt, pants, shorts or 
jumper. The code is technically optional until September, but school officials 
said most of the students are already wearing uniforms. Punishment for those 
who flout the code has not yet been established. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was surprised at how easy it was," said James Thomas, a coordinator for the 
magnet school. He said the school had been ready to deal with reluctant parents 
or rebellious students, but almost everyone was dressed according to code on 
the first day of classes, which began in early August because the school is on 
a year-round schedule. 
</P>
<P>
 One parent, Diane Fike, said she was glad her youngest son, who just started 
at Mary Butler as a fourth-grader, would be surrounded by navy and white. 
</P>
<P>
 "It really is a safety issue," Fike said. 
</P>
<P>
 "People in the community can really watch out for these kids when they're in 
uniform," she said. "Plus, I do think it's a social equalizer." 
</P>
<P>
 She said the students' gripes were to be expected: "Kids are going to want to 
do what they want to do." 
</P>
<P>
 Kirk Tyler, the 13-year-old Student Council president at Mary Butler, said he 
is wearing his uniform -- but reluctantly. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you get used to it now it won't become a big problem when you have to do 
it," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 But Kirk, an eighth-grader, still questioned the necessity of the dress code. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm going to learn if I'm going to learn," he said. "The clothes can't tell 
you that you're going to learn." 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't think you can really blame anything on clothes," he said, recalling a 
friend of his who had gotten into gang trouble. "It wasn't how he dressed, but 
how he treated people." 
</P>
<P>
 Some students, however, supported the dress code. 
</P>
<P>
 "I feel safer from all the gang violence and stuff," said Annie Laeardonn, an 
eighth-grader. 
</P>
<P>
 Many, though compliant, were less than enthusiastic. 
</P>
<P>
 "I want the freedom of what I wear," said Andrew Tully, 10, eating his lunch 
in a bright-colored T-shirt and shorts. "It's my 1st Amendment right." 
</P>
<P>
 In other parts of Southern California, there are other experiments with 
uniforms. At the new La Mesa Junior High in Santa Clarita, a pilot program has 
been implemented for seventh-graders, requiring them to wear clothing in the 
school colors of black, white and teal. Daniel Hanigan, the assistant 
superintendent of the district, said Wilson's signing the bill into law had 
been met with relief because the uniform policy was approved earlier in the 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 In Orange County, Santa Ana has 26 schools in which students may wear 
uniforms, the largest number in the area. Santa Ana administrators said they do 
not plan to make their programs mandatory. 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell, the UCLA dean, praised the law as "sort of an inoculation against 
controversy." 
</P>
<P>
 He also saw benefits in the Long Beach policy: "It relieves a certain kind of 
pressure we see in public schools -- what I have on as opposed to the things 
they ought to be focusing on, which is learning." 
</P>
<P>
 The trend also has ramifications for business. 
</P>
<P>
 Melissa Salazar, an employee at one of three Target stores in long Beach, said 
the store is selling hundreds of uniforms a day. But a manager of Chaktomouk 
fashions, which sells children's clothes in Long Beach, said sales are down by 
about $50 a day. 
</P>
<P>
 "I can deal with it," said Paul Cheng, the store manager. "I would sacrifice 
that amount of money to make a kid safer in their own school." 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writer Alicia DiRado and correspondents Mark Sabbatini and Eric 
Slater contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
