</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHITE HOUSE SEES CHANCES FADING FOR ACTION ON HEALTH; LEGISLATION: 
ADMINISTRATION TAKES MEASURES TO REVIVE DEBATE IN NEXT CONGRESS, SOURCES SAY. 
CLINTON REMAINS DETERMINED NOT TO SETTLE FOR HALF STEPS ON REFORM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN M. BRODER and EDWIN CHEN, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The White House is nearing the conclusion that action on meaningful health 
care reform is all but impossible this year and has begun laying the groundwork 
for moving the debate into the next session of Congress, according to 
Administration and congressional sources. 
</P>
<P>
 Even though officials continue to voice hope that Senate leaders can craft a 
workable compromise from two competing health care reform plans, time and 
tempers are growing short on Capitol Hill. The House already has left town 
after its rancorous debate on the crime bill, which is now stalled in the 
Senate, and there has been virtually no progress in recent weeks toward 
consensus on health care. 
</P>
<P>
 President Clinton remains determined not to settle for half steps on health 
care, which he believes may do more harm than good and doom chances for the 
sweeping reformation of the American health care system that he wants. 
</P>
<P>
 Unless the Senate can surmount numerous obstacles in the next few days and 
produce a bipartisan plan that makes significant progress toward universal 
health care coverage, the White House is prepared reluctantly to call it quits 
for this year, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 Clinton has discussed the prospect of suspending the health care debate until 
next year with several influential senators who share his concern about the 
chances of passing an even minimally acceptable bill this year. 
</P>
<P>
 And if Clinton's push for health care reform fails this year, aides are 
already planning how to present to the public the defeat of Clinton's central 
political promise and to contain the damage to the Clinton presidency. 
</P>
<P>
 The White House is expected to argue that health reform is not dead and that 
it will be revived when the next Congress convenes in January. Although the new 
Congress likely will have considerably more Republicans in both chambers than 
the current one, officials said that any health plan will require bipartisan 
support and fresh Republican minds may make the task easier rather than more 
difficult. 
</P>
<P>
 Clinton has repeatedly made the point in public that the "Brady bill" 
handgun-control measure took seven years to enact, anti-crime legislation has 
been pending for six years and the Americans With Disabilities Act required 
five years for passage. 
</P>
<P>
 An initiative as ambitious as the reform of one-seventh of the American 
economy cannot be expected to be implemented overnight, Clinton has said. 
</P>
<P>
 The White House is expected to attack congressional Republicans for blocking 
the Administration's health care plan and to challenge House and Senate GOP 
leaders to come up with a plan for providing health coverage for all Americans 
-- or explain why they are against it. 
</P>
<P>
 The Administration pitch will also cite substantial progress toward its goal: 
Health reform is now on the national front burner and the public expects 
action, the chief problems have been identified and countless hours have been 
spent drafting legislation and analyzing the benefits and liabilities of 
various proposals. 
</P>
<P>
 Clinton has said that, in all the debate over the various health plans now 
before Congress, his basic position has not changed. He is for comprehensive 
health benefits for all Americans, provided by private insurers and paid for 
through employer and worker contributions and savings from the existing system. 
</P>
<P>
 Anything less will not satisfy him and he would rather continue the debate 
next year than sign a bill that falls short of his fundamental goals, he 
insisted again Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you are asking me where I am, I am still where I always was," Clinton told 
the international convention of B'nai B'rith in Chicago in a satellite hookup. 
</P>
<P>
 "The main thing we must do is we must do something that will work and it will 
be better not to do anything at all than to adopt a program that would actually 
increase costs of health care and reduce coverage. That's what we don't want to 
do," Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
 White House officials concede that the prospects for action this year are 
growing dimmer by the day. Even upbeat public pronouncements are qualified now. 
</P>
<P>
 Asked whether Clinton expects an acceptable bill this year, White House Press 
Secretary Dee Dee Myers said Wednesday: "Well, I think he's hopeful as he has 
been throughout this process. Certainly it's difficult. He knew from the 
beginning it would be very, very difficult." 
</P>
<P>
 Harold M. Ickes, the White House deputy chief of staff who is overseeing 
health care strategy, insisted in an interview with wire service reporters that 
"health care is alive and well," despite the assertion Tuesday by House Speaker 
Thomas S. Foley (D-Wash.) that Congress was unlikely to enact anything beyond 
incremental health insurance reforms this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think the predictions that this is going to be shut down are -- there's no 
basis for that," Ickes said. But, he acknowledged, "there's no question that 
the clock is running against us." 
</P>
<P>
 In the Senate, members of the bipartisan "mainstream" coalition and their 
aides continued meeting throughout the day, putting the finishing touches on a 
plan that they intend to be an alternative to the bill proposed by Majority 
Leader George J. Mitchell (D-Me.). 
</P>
<P>
 One coalition member, Sen. David L. Boren (D-Okla.), said late Wednesday 
afternoon that the group expected to finish its work Wednesday night in time to 
send the proposal to the Congressional Budget Office for analysis. 
</P>
<P>
 As the group of about 20 senators and their staffs worked in a stuffy room 
just off the Capitol Rotunda, members were grimly aware that the window of 
opportunity for enacting health reform was closing. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's getting late," said Sen. Nancy Landon Kassebaum (R-Kan.). 
</P>
<P>
 Sen. Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.) added: "I think we're within a few days of just 
putting the whole health care issue to bed for the year." 
</P>
<P>
 Separately, Minority Leader Bob Dole (R-Kan.) agreed with that assessment. 
"Time is ticking away," he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
 Aside from substantive differences between the "mainstream" coalition plan and 
Mitchell's, another potential obstacle toward some compromise is that most of 
the bipartisan group members are insisting that their plan be, in Kassebaum's 
words, "a separate package." 
</P>
<P>
 By that, they mean that they want their proposal to be considered as an 
alternative to Mitchell's. 
</P>
<P>
 Mitchell's bill, backed by the White House, aims to attain 95% coverage by the 
year 2000, relying on voluntary measures and a variety of insurance reforms and 
subsidies to the needy. It would trigger an employer mandate by 2002 in states 
that do not achieve 95% coverage, requiring large businesses to pay at least 
50% of a worker's premiums. 
</P>
<P>
 The "mainstream" coalition's plan, unveiled Friday evening, eliminates the 
employer mandate altogether and would trim $400 billion from future growth of 
Medicare and Medicaid over 10 years to generate funds to help poor people buy 
health insurance. It aims for about 91% coverage by the year 2002. 
</P>
<P>
 Both plans call for a number of insurance market reforms, barring insurers 
from denying or canceling coverage on the basis of a customer's health. All 
health plans would be available to all applicants and policy renewals would be 
guaranteed. 
</P>
<P>
 The discussion over the next few days will hinge on whether the coalition bill 
can be combined in some way with the Mitchell plan into a coherent package 
acceptable to a majority in the Senate and to Clinton. On that effort hangs the 
fate of health reform this year. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's all a judgment call by the Democratic leadership," said Sen. Dave 
Durenberger (R-Minn.). 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writer Karen Tumulty contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
