803 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CAPITOL JOURNAL: WILSON'S VIEW OF A 2ND TERM AS HE TURNS 61 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GEORGE SKELTON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It was Gov. Pete Wilson's 61st birthday Tuesday, but governors don't really 
get to celebrate such milestones, not in a normal sense. Especially if they're 
in a tight race for reelection. They're leery of taking any R & R for fear of 
losing a step to the enemy. 
</P>
<P>
 Not that this governor couldn't use some rest. Aides say he survives on four 
to five hours sleep a night and is prone to calling them at any hour. The 
failure to recharge leaves him sometimes running only on adrenaline and 
delivering long-winded, rambling speeches. And by the look of his ashen face, 
it's obvious his only outdoor recreation is photo-ops. 
</P>
<P>
 But he's "healthy as an ox," advisers say. He exercises indoors. And by the 
look in his eyes, it's clear there's energy to burn and an unflinching focus on 
the main target: reelection. 
</P>
<P>
 So on this birthday, he'd make do with the presentation of a chocolate cake 
and bottle of Cakebread Cabernet from the legislative leaders, a surprise 
arranged by Assembly Speaker Willie Brown (D-San Francisco). "My leadership 
buddies," the governor deadpanned later. That night, he'd fly to Del Mar 
racetrack for a birthday dinner with 650 of his closest friends who could 
contribute $250 apiece to his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
 And his staff would book him for lunch at a popular capital restaurant 
(Dawson's) with a columnist who wanted to ask what a second term might be like. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 There were a lot of "Hi, how are ya's" from surprised lobbyists as the 
governor walked across the street and was seated at a back corner table. In 
summary, this is what he said between sips of a nonalcoholic beer and bites of 
a Caesar salad with crab meat: 
</P>
<P>
 Water (California's biggest perennial problem, but an issue being ignored) -- 
In a second term, he'd try to get agriculture, urban users and 
environmentalists "to make some sense" and compromise. "We're going to continue 
to grow, whether anybody likes it or not. The need will increase for water." 
The solution is conservation, more off-stream storage reservoirs and the 
ability to privately sell water. It's also "probably true" there needs to be a 
better way of moving water through the Delta. But he doesn't seem ready to 
fight for a controversial Peripheral Canal. 
</P>
<P>
 Environmentalists -- The "least realistic" among them are "willing to allow 
the Endangered Species Act to divert" water from farming and industry. "Honest 
science" is needed to determine exactly what's required to save a "significant 
species." And he distinguishes between significant (such as salmon) and 
insignificant, saying, "One of the candidates (for protection) that seriously 
threatens jobs in the Central Valley is the fairy shrimp. It's about a 
centimeter long. It's found in drainage ditches in 23 counties. Now, for that 
to interfere with development or grazing raises serious questions about whether 
people are rational. I'm sure it's part of somebody's food chain, but. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
 Taxes -- He "absolutely" won't raise taxes ever again. "You don't have to read 
my lips, read history." Since 1991, when he raised taxes to balance a 
recession-plagued budget, he's opposed all tax hikes. In fact, "it's fairly 
likely" there could be a tax cut "because I'm convinced we're going to see a 
tremendous increase in employment." 
</P>
<P>
 Business -- He'd push bills to "undo the regulatory excess." California needs 
to get more competitive "so we can increase revenues and make investments in 
education and public safety, the two essentials." 
</P>
<P>
 Schools/Crime -- The worst classroom culprit is lack of parental motivation, 
which is "much more important than money." Too often this results from teen 
pregnancy and babies reared without fathers. "There's no civilizing, 
socializing influence. . . . The 14-year-old mothers produce 16-year-old 
predators. Gang members." He already has provided welfare bonuses for teen 
mothers who stay in school and penalties for those who don't. 
</P>
<P>
 "You want to know what I want to do in a second term? A dozen things. But I 
tell you what we have got to do because it's at the root. . . . Teen pregnancy 
can lead to a career on welfare and a gang member-son . . . a major cost in 
human suffering and dollars." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 We also naturally talked about the governor's enemy : Treasurer Kathleen 
Brown. 
</P>
<P>
 "She seems phony," he said. "She's sent very mixed signals. She's trying to 
sound like me. But she lacks credentials. She has no record in law enforcement, 
no record in. . . ." 
</P>
<P>
 Wait. Ronald Reagan also had no record when he ran against Pat Brown in 1966. 
"But he was offering people a clear choice," Wilson said, "and running against 
an honest liberal, who, unlike his children, never professed to be anything but 
a liberal." 
</P>
<P>
 I was tempted to ask about Brown's charges of broken promises in his first 
term. But that could wait. Even a governor deserves some break on his birthday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
