<HEADLINE>
<P>
O.C. LEADERS HOPEFUL AFTER RAMS TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG HERNANDEZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The proposal presented to the Los Angeles Rams on Wednesday by a committee 
that is trying to keep the team in Orange County drew a cautiously hopeful 
reaction from city, business and civic leaders. 
</P>
<P>
 Mayor Tom Daly said the plan could be a "major step forward" if the Rams show 
interest in it. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's a sound package, and it can be the basis for a new partnership 
between the Rams and the Orange County community," Daly said. 
</P>
<P>
 Members of the Save the Rams task force, made up of dozens of local business 
people and elected officials, are hoping to entice the Rams to stay in Orange 
County with a proposal to refurbish Anaheim Stadium. The group has also 
proposed to build a new training facility and corporate headquarters for the 
team in Orange. In addition, the proposal includes purchase of a minority 
interest in the team, which would provide the Rams with a $50-million infusion 
of cash. 
</P>
<P>
 Daly said the Save the Rams plan is realistic from the city's standpoint, 
although "most of the pieces of the package are conceptual and there are still 
a lot of details to work out." 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Irv Pickler said he is supportive of the proposal as long as the 
city does not have to bear the brunt of it financially. 
</P>
<P>
 "The city of Anaheim does not have any money," Pickler said. "But as long as I 
can see a funding source, I have no problem with what's been proposed. I think 
it's an impressive offer and something any good team would and should look at." 
</P>
<P>
 But Pickler said he is still doubtful that the NFL franchise will stay in 
town. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just have a feeling that it's not going to happen, although I hope that it 
does," he said. "If we can get some reaction from the Rams, everyone will jump 
with joy." 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim Chamber of Commerce officials said they were impressed with the 
package but pessimistic that it will entice the team to stay. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're realistic," said interim executive director Jay Walton. "I wouldn't bet 
the farm, but we are hopeful that this will succeed." 
</P>
<P>
 Walt Disney Co. officials said the proposal is a solid one and should make the 
team stop and take notice. 
</P>
<P>
 "How can they not at least pay attention now?" said Ron Dominguez, executive 
vice president of Walt Disney attractions. "I think the deal presented gives 
the Rams a lot to consider. It shows that there is a lot of belief in them in 
the community. They should have a sense that they are welcome here and that 
this community wants them here." 
</P>
<P>
 Rams Booster Club President Frank Bryant, a member of the Save the Rams 
committee, said the proposal is filled with "excellent ideas." 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm hoping it will cause (the team) to stop and reconsider and maybe start 
negotiating," Bryant said. "If they do that, then we have accomplished a lot." 
</P>
<P>
 Most leaders praised the efforts of the Save the Rams committee, which they 
said completed its work in a remarkably short period. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think the group did a phenomenal job," Pickler said. "They have tried 
everything. If this doesn't do it, my hat is still off to them. They have been 
dedicated and sincere and pulled out all the stops to get the team to say yes." 
</P>
</TEXT>
