740 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
JIM MURRAY: KIRALY IS ON THE BALL ON THE SAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JIM MURRAY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 If he were in basketball, they'd call him "Magic." In baseball, he'd be "the 
Man" or maybe even "the Thumper." In tennis, he might be "Boom Boom." In golf, 
maybe "the Hawk." 
</P>
<P>
 He'd probably have a shoe contract like Air Jordan -- except his sport doesn't 
wear shoes. Like Lawrence of Arabia, his domain is the burning sand. He has 
been in more sand than a camel. 
</P>
<P>
 What he is, is kind of a complicated beachcomber. Oh, he doesn't spend his 
time waiting for the copra boat or even searching for the perfect wave. He 
spends more time at the beach than a sea gull. If it weren't for sunblock, he'd 
probably be a char. 
</P>
<P>
 He plays a court game but he doesn't need a racket. In his case, the racket 
has five fingers and comes attached. And the ball is not this fuzzy little 
thing about the size of an orange, it's a big leather ball about the size of a 
soccer ball. Hitting it can have all the thrills of smashing a fist into a 
cement block wall. 
</P>
<P>
 The players call him "Double-K" or just "KK" as in killer. His game is 
volleyball and he just might be the best there is at it at the moment, if you 
count the evidence of two Olympic gold medals, more than 90 open titles and 
$1.57 million in prize money. 
</P>
<P>
 Karch Kiraly (pronounced "Kar-eye') is one of those guys they'll name a trophy 
or award after one of these years. Like the Cy Young in baseball or the Lady 
Byng in hockey, the Kiraly will stand for consistent excellence. There'll be 
legends. Some day, they'll tell you he had the vertical jump of a springbok and 
that he once spiked a ball so deep in the sand they never found it. 
</P>
<P>
 Although a lot of people are surprised to find it out, volleyball is as 
American an invention as apple pie. But, while it never seemed to make much 
headway in its home country, it grew by leaps and bounds overseas. 
</P>
<P>
 But what really moved the sport out of agate type and onto Page 1 (and Channel 
9) was the beach version. 
</P>
<P>
 It historically was played indoors like basketball and hockey -- a six-player 
game that, between Olympics and like the javelin throw, didn't have much total 
impact on the sports scene. 
</P>
<P>
 It began to be played recreationally on the Southern California littoral by 
the hang-10 hunks looking for something to do waiting for the surf to be up. 
The two-man game caught on at once. Instead of the five-set marathons of the 
indoor games, it had a one-set war that had all the urgency and high excitement 
of sudden death. Television even insisted on a clock that limited a game to 
nine minutes of playing time or about one hour of elapsed time. 
</P>
<P>
 It was perceived as a kind of dilettante sport. Not polo, exactly, but not 
Dempsey-Tunney or Ali-Frazier, either. But it did have its scent of 
head-to-head competition of, say, Budge-Perry or Sampras-Becker. The players 
made prizefighters look flabby.  
</P>
<P>
 Basketball grabbed the headlines with its "Mr. Clutches" and "Big O's and Big 
E's and Big Dippers" and "Magics and Air Jordans" while volleyball got its 
audiences from people looking for seashells or places to stick the umbrellas. 
</P>
<P>
 But all that changed when television people came sniffing around for product. 
They liked what they saw. The ball was highly visible, no hockey puck here. The 
action was constant, the bodies were all hard, the game glamorous.  
</P>
<P>
 The graph could only go up. The beach game caught on as the hardcourt version 
languished and you had incongruities like entrepreneurs bringing in truckloads 
of sand and dumping them on the floor of Madison Square Garden. They'd recreate 
the beach at Santa Monica in places like Cincinnati, where the only surf was 
the Ohio River. 
</P>
<P>
 Kiraly learned the game on the golden sands of Santa Barbara, but he was not 
your basic son of the rich. Dad had gotten out of Hungary one jump ahead of 
Khrushchev's tanks in the Budapest uprising of 1956 and fled to America, where 
he became a civil engineer and then a doctor. 
</P>
<P>
 There were never any white flags in the Kiraly family as Soviet marksmen could 
attest, and Karch plays the kind of all-court game that moved an opponent to 
blurt, "Why is it with K you feel you have your back to the wall when you're up 
11-2?" 
</P>
<P>
 He and partner Kent Steffes have won 14 of 18 tournaments this year and go in 
as favorites at the $1-million Miller Lite Championships at Hermosa Beach this 
weekend, with $100,000 going to the winning team as well as dispersal of 
$750,000 in bonus money for the entire season. 
</P>
<P>
 That's a lot of money to make in your bare feet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
