<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: LA HABRA; CITY TO CONSIDER RENAMING PARK AREA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIMI KO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Council members next month will consider renaming part of Portola Park 
after the late Jesse Flores, a former major league pitcher and renowned scout 
who lived in the city from 1923 until his death in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
 Flores, who was 77 when he died, moved to the city from Mexico with his family 
when he was 8. After years of playing sandlot baseball in what is now Portola 
Park, Flores became the third Mexican American player -- the first Mexican 
American pitcher -- in the major leagues in 1942. 
</P>
<P>
 Mel Almada, a center fielder, and Chile Gomez, a second baseman, were the 
first and second Mexican Americans in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
 Flores played for the Chicago Cubs, Philadelphia Athletics and the Cleveland 
Indians in the major leagues and the Los Angeles Angels, San Diego Padres, 
Oakland Oaks, Sacramento Solons and the Portland Beavers in the Pacific Coast 
League for 17 years. 
</P>
<P>
 He spent the last 30 years of his life scouting for the Minnesota Twins and 
the Pittsburgh Pirates. 
</P>
<P>
 Throughout his career, Flores spent his off-season time developing baseball 
programs for local youths and adults. He organized a semipro baseball team, the 
La Habra Tigers, and managed it. He supplied the baseballs and bats and spent 
Sunday mornings watering and preparing a field at Portola Park for afternoon 
games. 
</P>
<P>
 Residents remember Flores for teaching his players the fundamentals of the 
game and for inspiring a sense of leadership, discipline and fairness. 
</P>
<P>
 "Jesse was a real good man, a friendly man to everybody. He did a lot for the 
youth of this city and he deserves to have something named after him," said 
Magdaleno Aguilar, who grew up on 4th Street -- the same street Flores lived 
on. "I used to go watch Jesse and the Tigers play at Portola Park all the time. 
He was an inspiration." 
</P>
<P>
 Aguilar requested that the city rename Portola Park the Jesse Flores Park or 
name a baseball field there in Flores' honor. 
</P>
<P>
 A decision is expected at the Sept. 15 meeting.MIMI KOBASEBALL PLAY 
</P>
</TEXT>
