<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SOUTH GATE; POLICE CENTER AT TARGET STORE OFFERS SAFETY TIPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SIMON ROMERO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Carjacking prevention hint No. 8: If a suspicious person approaches your car, 
police say, drive away quickly and carefully -- even if you must go through a 
red light. 
</P>
<P>
 In a move exemplifying cooperation between the private and public sectors, 
police last week opened a police information center in the busy parking lot of 
the Target store at 5700 Firestone Ave. to make crime prevention tips more 
readily available to the public. 
</P>
<P>
 The center, located in a trailer under the Target sign, will be open three or 
four days a week, depending on staff availability, said Police Chief Ron 
George. In addition to providing residents with information on preventing 
crimes such as carjacking and kidnaping, the center will serve as a meeting 
point for area police, who can use the facility to prepare reports and 
communicate with headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
 The staff will also provide bicycle safety classes. Officers will not be able 
to detain crime suspects at the center. 
</P>
<P>
 At grand opening festivities replete with beauty queens, area politicians and 
a police robot called Sparky -- George lauded the new center: "This is a 
win-win situation. The city wins, since its awareness of crime prevention 
increases, and Target wins, since it gains a police presence on its property," 
he said to 40 people on hand for the ribbon-cutting ceremony.  
</P>
<P>
 In the second experiment of this kind, Target is paying all of the police 
center's expenses. Last year, Long Beach police established a center at 
Target's store at 950 E. 33rd St. in that city. SIMON ROMERO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
